01:47:14,301 --> 01:47:16,501
That's something I'd stay up late for.
Definitely.

1936
01:47:16,601 --> 01:47:18,601
I thought so.

1937
01:47:22,301 --> 01:47:24,426
You know, I don't get it.

1938
01:47:25,201 --> 01:47:28,801
All this psychobabble in the media.

1939
01:47:29,201 --> 01:47:33,251
I mean, all I wanted to do
is make this a better and safer world...

1940
01:47:33,351 --> 01:47:35,351
...for everyone.

1941
01:47:36,001 --> 01:47:37,901
There's good and there's evil.

1942
01:47:38,001 --> 01:47:43,801
And you and I and the rest of the
people in America know the difference.

1943
01:47:43,901 --> 01:47:46,451
That good ultimately wins out.

1944
01:47:49,401 --> 01:47:53,351
But you have to fight for it.
You have to fight for it.

1945
01:47:53,451 --> 01:47:58,001
People have no idea how hard it is on us.

1946
01:47:59,901 --> 01:48:02,601
The sacrifices you've made.

1947
01:48:02,901 --> 01:48:06,601
Laura, I knew when I married you
what you were made of.

1948
01:48:06,701 --> 01:48:09,951
That same bolt of lightning hit both of us.

1949
01:48:10,051 --> 01:48:12,051
For better or worse.

1950
01:48:12,101 --> 01:48:14,201
Mostly better.

1951
01:48:18,701 --> 01:48:21,101
Since the start of the war, though...

1952
01:48:21,201 --> 01:48:24,901
...I barely have time
to run my three miles anymore.

1953
01:48:25,001 --> 01:48:26,101
My knees hurt.

1954
01:48:26,201 --> 01:48:28,601
I'm just off my pace.

1955
01:48:29,701 --> 01:48:31,801
It's been hard on me, Laura.

1956
01:48:31,901 --> 01:48:34,401
On top of everything else.

1957
01:48:34,501 --> 01:48:36,501
Well...

1958
01:48:36,701 --> 01:48:39,421
...someday the war will be over.

1959
01:48:39,601 --> 01:48:42,236
And we can have our lives back.

1960
01:48:44,901 --> 01:48:48,046
I'll get those tickets for next week.

1961
01:48:54,801 --> 01:48:57,901
Poppy, what are you doing here?
- I used to sit in this chair.

1962
01:48:58,001 --> 01:49:00,001
Opposite Baker.

1963
01:49:01,701 --> 01:49:07,141
Got him to help pull your ass
out of the fire in Florida in 2000.

1964
01:49:07,301 --> 01:49:09,301
Don't forget that.

1965
01:49:10,001 --> 01:49:11,401
Come on. Let's go.

1966
01:49:11,501 --> 01:49:13,901
A little mano a mano.

1967
01:49:15,301 --> 01:49:18,401
Bet you I can still whip your ass.
- What?

1968
01:49:18,501 --> 01:49:22,101
Got to admit, I scared you back then.
Still scare you, don't I?

1969
01:49:22,201 --> 01:49:27,046
I got a lot on my mind.
I don't need this, Poppy. Not now.

1970
01:49:30,201 --> 01:49:32,241
Why you being so ornery?

1971
01:49:32,301 --> 01:49:34,501
Because you disappoint me, Junior.

1972
01:49:34,601 --> 01:49:36,401
Deeply disappoint me.

1973
01:49:36,501 --> 01:49:39,201
After all these years. Still?

1974
01:49:39,301 --> 01:49:41,801
You're still with that?
- No, no, no.

1975
01:49:41,901 --> 01:49:45,101
Not the girls or summer jobs anymore.

1976
01:49:47,501 --> 01:49:50,651
I dug myself out of the depths of hell
to stand on my own two feet...

1977
01:49:50,751 --> 01:49:53,401
...make something of myself.
And I did it on my own.

1978
01:49:53,501 --> 01:49:54,901
Think you did.

1979
01:49:55,001 --> 01:49:57,001
Yeah, well, you also wrecked it.

1980
01:49:57,101 --> 01:49:58,501
Wrecked. Wrecked what?

1981
01:49:58,601 --> 01:50:00,401
You've ruined it for us.

1982
01:50:00,501 --> 01:50:02,801
What are you talking about?
- The Bush name.

1983
01:50:02,901 --> 01:50:04,001
Get out of my office.

1984
01:50:04,101 --> 01:50:06,801
Two hundred years of work. For Jeb.

1985
01:50:06,901 --> 01:50:08,601
Get out.

1986
01:50:08,701 --> 01:50:11,651
With this fiasco.

1987
01:50:11,751 --> 01:50:13,101
Get out of my life.

1988
01:50:13,201 --> 01:50:15,201
And that's what it is.

1989
01:50:15,201 --> 01:50:16,501
A goddamn fiasco.

1990
01:50:16,601 --> 01:50:18,101
Get out.

1991
01:50:18,201 --> 01:50:20,601
George. George.

1992
01:50:21,301 --> 01:50:22,701
Are you all right?

1993
01:50:22,801 --> 01:50:24,801
Oh, Jesus.

1994
01:50:24,801 --> 01:50:27,101
Jesus, George.

1995
01:50:31,401 --> 01:50:33,701
There's been tough weeks in Iraq.

1996
01:50:33,801 --> 01:50:35,701
But our central commitment
of the mission...

1997
01:50:35,801 --> 01:50:40,731
...is the transfer of sovereignty
back to the Iraqi people.

1998
01:50:41,001 --> 01:50:43,701
Now, we've set a deadline
for this to take place...

1999
01:50:43,801 --> 01:50:45,701
...three months from now.

2000
01:50:45,801 --> 01:50:49,101
June 30, 2004.

2001
01:50:55,501 --> 01:50:59,921
It's important that
we meet that deadline, all right?

2002
01:51:01,201 --> 01:51:03,411
The only way we can win...

2003
01:51:05,401 --> 01:51:09,001
...is to leave before the job is done.

2004
01:51:10,401 --> 01:51:12,401
Yeah.

2005
01:51:12,701 --> 01:51:14,001
I'll now take questions.

2006
01:51:14,101 --> 01:51:15,101
Mr. President.
- Sir.

2007
01:51:15,201 --> 01:51:16,701
Sir, sir.
- Question, sir.

2008
01:51:16,801 --> 01:51:18,801
Yeah.

2009
01:51:19,501 --> 01:51:20,901
Miss China?

2010
01:51:21,001 --> 01:51:23,401
Mr. President,
I know this is a tough question...

2011
01:51:23,501 --> 01:51:26,551
...but my viewers would really like to know.

2012
01:51:26,651 --> 01:51:29,201
What place do you think
you'll have in history?

2013
01:51:29,301 --> 01:51:31,301
In history?

2014
01:51:32,101 --> 01:51:33,501
I don't know.

2015
01:51:33,601 --> 01:51:36,001
In history, we'll all be dead.

2016
01:51:36,101 --> 01:51:38,101
Mr. President?
- Yeah.

2017
01:51:38,501 --> 01:51:41,001
Mr. President?
- Yeah, John, there.

2018
01:51:41,101 --> 01:51:43,001
Thank you, sir. Mr. President.
- Yeah.

2019
01:51:43,101 --> 01:51:47,501
After 9l11, what would you say
your biggest mistakes would be...

2020
01:51:47,601 --> 01:51:51,511
...and what lessons
have you learned from them?

2021
01:51:57,901 --> 01:51:59,601
Now, I wish you would have given me...

2022
01:51:59,701 --> 01:52:03,356
...this written question beforehand,
John...

2023
01:52:03,701 --> 01:52:06,166
...so I could prepare for it.

2024
01:52:09,401 --> 01:52:11,401
You know, I just...

2025
01:52:15,801 --> 01:52:18,901
John, I'm sure historians will say,
'Gosh,' you know.

2026
01:52:19,001 --> 01:52:24,441
'I wish he could've done better,
you know, this way or that way.'

2027
01:52:29,301 --> 01:52:32,251
Something will pop into my head
here in the press conference...

2028
01:52:32,351 --> 01:52:35,201
...with all the pressure of trying
to come up with an answer...

2029
01:52:35,301 --> 01:52:37,301
...but it hasn't yet.

2030
01:52:40,301 --> 01:52:42,301
You know, I hope...

2031
01:52:42,601 --> 01:52:45,701
I don't wanna sound like
I haven't made no mistakes.

2032
01:52:45,801 --> 01:52:48,201
You know, I'm confident I have.

2033
01:52:48,301 --> 01:52:50,301
It's just, I haven't...

2034
01:52:52,201 --> 01:52:54,401
You know, you really put me
on the spot here...

2035
01:52:54,501 --> 01:52:55,601
...and maybe I'm not...

2036
01:52:55,701 --> 01:53:00,716
...as quick on my feet
as I should be in coming up with one.

2037
01:53:21,201 --> 01:53:22,401
Mr. President.

2038
01:53:22,501 --> 01:53:25,301
Not now, Ari. Not now. I'm busy.

2039
01:53:34,401 --> 01:53:38,001
We're locked into a dandy, 1- 1 here, 
bottom of the eighth, two outs...

2040
01:53:38,101 --> 01:53:39,501
...as Spencer stands in.

2041
01:53:39,601 --> 01:53:41,401
He's 3-for-3 on the night.

2042
01:53:41,501 --> 01:53:44,101
This is the first time he's come up
with a man on base.

2043
01:53:44,201 --> 01:53:45,801
He hasn't had a chance to do damage.

2044
01:53:45,901 --> 01:53:48,001
He'd certainly love to do some here.

2045
01:53:48,101 --> 01:53:51,001
Monroe off of first. That was
the starting pitcher by the way.

2046
01:53:51,101 --> 01:53:53,201
Jay Fletcher you just saw down
in the bullpen.

2047
01:53:53,301 --> 01:53:54,501
Woodhouse is on deck.

2048
01:53:54,601 --> 01:53:56,601
Schwartz will follow if we get that far.

2049
01:53:56,701 --> 01:53:58,901
Chavez now from the stretch.

2050
01:53:59,001 --> 01:54:00,601
And the pitch to Monroe.

2051
01:54:00,701 --> 01:54:03,201
Swinging, there's a fly ball into right field.

2052
01:54:03,301 --> 01:54:04,601
Moving over.

2053
01:54:04,701 --> 01:54:06,101
He dives, he misses the ball.

2054
01:54:06,201 --> 01:54:08,401
Monroe rounds first.
He heads for second.

2055
01:54:08,501 --> 01:54:11,101
And here comes Spencer
around third going for home.

2056
01:54:11,201 --> 01:54:12,801
The relay to the plate is...

2057
01:54:12,901 --> 01:54:16,981
